   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28598_1817_08_01_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName>Edgeworth's Town</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1817-08-01">August 1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi>. 1817.</date>
               </dateline>
               <lb/>
               <salute>
                  My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">friend</persName>,<lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>It is long since I have felt so much<lb/>
               satisfaction as I felt this morning<lb/>
               from your letter. Both <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               <add>my aunts</add> and I thought we might feel sure<lb/>
               <del>that</del> of what your opinion would<lb/>
               be, but to have that opinion so fully<lb/>
               and clearly expressed, to see the<lb/>
               reasons by which it is supported<lb/>
               so ably stated &amp; to feel at once that<lb/>
               they are perfectly solid and that<lb/>
               they entirely coincide with my own<lb/>
               is highly satisfactory <del>to me</del> - I told<lb/>
               you truly, that I was conscious that<lb/>
               I should not have been able to act<lb/>
               in consequence of your opinion<lb/>
               had it been contrary to my own<lb/>
               - that no power but that which can<lb/>
               never more be exerted over my mind<lb/>
               could even if I were convinced it<lb/>
               were right &amp; necessary <del/> excite<lb/>
               me at this time to such an attempt<lb/>
               - But the more I felt that your opinion<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28598_1817_08_01_page02.jpg"/>
               
               had it been on the other side of the question<lb/>
               would have been inadequate to rouse<lb/>
               me to exertion above my <del/> powers<lb/>
               the more I felt anxious that such<lb/>
               should not be the opinion of the<lb/>
               friend whose judgment I know <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">my<lb/>
               dear father</persName> valued above that of any<lb/>
               other of his friends and upon whose<lb/>
               personal attachment, knowledge of<lb/>
               his character and regard for his <choice>
                  <orig>me-<lb/>
               -mory</orig>
                  <reg>memory</reg>
               </choice> he relied more than upon<lb/>
               those of any other man living - <choice>
                  <orig>ex<lb/>
               -cept</orig>
                  <reg>except</reg>
               </choice> his own sons -<lb/>
               I thank you particularly for stating<lb/>
               all your reasons distinctly as <hi rend="underline">your</hi>
               <lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">own</hi>, without reference to my sentiments.<lb/>
               - I shall have to consult you probably<lb/>
               hereafter on many points - <del>and</del> so<lb/>
               once for all, be assured that you can<lb/>
               never speak the truth to me too flatly<lb/>
               or too strongly - Consider I have been<lb/>
               used to it - and used to feel it the surest<lb/>
               proof of friendship -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>You have relieved me from all<lb/>
               remaining <del>fear</del>
               <add>scruple</add> of dis-obeying that<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">injunction</hi> with which I never <hi rend="underline">promised </hi>
               <lb/>
               to comply - which it was dreadful to me<lb/>
               to hear- and <hi rend="underline">to</hi>
               <hi rend="underline">recollect</hi> - still more dreadful.<lb/>
               - I am glad that you coolly &amp; at a distance<lb/>
               agree with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. E</persName> and me that it was a feverish<lb/>
               feeling<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28598_1817_08_01_page03.jpg"/>
               
               which dictated that letter to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName> - How<lb/>
               I rejoice that I did not send it - and<lb/>
               yet at the time I feared I was doing wrong<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>But as you say dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> I<lb/>
               must not ever more permit myself to<lb/>
               think of that injunction - I must emulate<lb/>
               "<hi rend="underline">his</hi> strength of resolution which rejected<lb/>
               "all minor views incompatible with<lb/>
               "a great object. - How kind of you to say<lb/>
               that "Could he now look down upon<lb/>
               "the struggles of my heart he would<lb/>
               "cheer me on &amp; encourage me to do that<lb/>
               "which in my conscience I judge most fit"<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>It seems as if you had looked<lb/>
               straight to the bottom of my heart for<lb/>
               this is the idea the question that<lb/>
               perpetually reccurs to me<lb/>
               "If he could look down upon<lb/>
               "me - could see me now what would<lb/>
               "he think - would he approve or <choice>
                  <orig>disap-<lb/>
                  "-prove</orig>
                  <reg>disprove</reg>
               </choice>.? -<lb/>
               On the question touched upon in the<lb/>
               conclusion of your letter - should the<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Memoi1">Memoirs</title> be in his own person &amp; as<lb/>
               written by him? - I differ from you- - But<lb/>
               we shall have time &amp; time enough to<lb/>
               discuss this hereafter - we differ only<lb/>
               because you do not know the facts - and<lb/>
               have not seen the <choice>
                  <abbr>M<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>
                  </abbr>
                  <reg>messages</reg>
               </choice>- <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. E</persName> has read<lb/>
               it all and agrees with me - I had never<lb/>
               had the courage to <del>read</del> open it till two days<lb/>
               ago when I felt the propriety the necessity<lb/>
               of my two aunts seeing it &amp; of hearing their<lb/>
               opinion on the points that <hi rend="underline">peculiarly concern</hi>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28598_1817_08_01_page04.jpg"/>
               <hi rend="underline">their family</hi> before they should leave us -<lb/>
               I could not <hi rend="underline">send</hi> the <choice>
                  <abbr>M<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>.</abbr>
                  <reg>messages</reg>
               </choice> to them - Their<lb/>
               eyes are both so bad that they could not<lb/>
               read the <choice>
                  <abbr>M<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>.</abbr>
                  <reg>messages</reg>
               </choice> to themselves - There was<lb/>
               no alternative - I had the resolution to<lb/>
               begin to read it to them myself - An hour<lb/>
               every day they are to come to my room -<lb/>
               for this purpose - The first hour you may<lb/>
               conceive touched us exceedingly - But<lb/>
               it was <hi rend="underline">satisfactory</hi> to us all - When<lb/>
               you see the M<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>. which you certainly shall<lb/>
               see, your judgment will, I can almost<lb/>
               venture to say I am certain, agree<lb/>
               with ours - as far as we have gone -<lb/>
               - As to the main point that it should be<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">his own</hi> I have no doubt - If I find<lb/>
               any thing that I think or that you think<lb/>
               right to be omitted I will <del>
                  <hi rend="underline">omit</hi>
               </del>
               <hi rend="underline">expunge</hi>
               <lb/>
               but I will not <hi rend="underline">alter</hi>
               <del>a word</del> any passage<lb/>
               or change any sentiment - <hi rend="underline">that</hi> I should<lb/>
               think a dereliction of my duty &amp; breaking<lb/>
               a sacred trust -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>But I will restrain myself from <choice>
                  <orig>en-<lb/>
                  tering</orig>
                  <reg>entering</reg>
               </choice> more into a question which we<lb/>
               shall have time hereafter I hope to discuss<lb/>
               I entirely agree (I scarcely need say) I<lb/>
               agree with you as to the time of publication<lb/>
               - Thank God - you think so<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I employ myself &amp; have <choice>
                  <orig>em-<lb/>
                  ployed</orig>
                  <reg>employed</reg>
               </choice> myself unremittingly for some<lb/>
               hours every morning since I returned<lb/>
               home in reading over his incomparable<lb/>
               letters <add>on public subjects</add> &amp; those of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DayX2">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Day</persName> which he had <choice>
                  <orig>permiss-<lb/>
                  ion</orig>
                  <reg>permission</reg>
               </choice> to publish <del>&amp;</del> I have expunged all<lb/>
               passages<lb/>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28598_1817_08_01_page05.jpg"/>
               
               that ought to be expunged &amp; marked such<lb/>
               of the very few letters as I think fit to be<lb/>
               used - I have written my opinion on<lb/>
               each &amp; arranged them so that if I were<lb/>
               to die before I could <del>com</del> fulfil the trust<lb/>
               reposed in me, at least I shall have<lb/>
               done something towards it &amp; all that<lb/>
               I could do -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Before poor <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StaeA1">Madame de Stael</persName>
               <lb/>
               lost her faculties it must have been<lb/>
               a delightful satisfaction to her that<lb/>
               she had finished her life of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NeckJ1">her father</persName>
               <lb/>
               - I am in excellent health and<lb/>
               not in the least apprehensive that my<lb/>
               health should fail - on the contrary<lb/>
               I hav<gap/> felt it strengthen under the<lb/>
               pre<gap/> which I sh.<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> sometime time ago<lb/>
               have thought would have overwhelmed<lb/>
               it - But tho I am in good health <hi rend="underline">now</hi>
               <lb/>
               human life is so uncertain that I feel<lb/>
               it <del>a</del>
               <add>an <unclear>imperious</unclear>
               </add> duty in this instance not to <choice>
                  <orig>procras-<lb/>
                  -tinate</orig>
                  <reg>procrastinate</reg>
               </choice> - &amp; all that I can do I will</p>
            <lb/>
            <closer>
               I am your grateful friend<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName> -<lb/>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28598_1817_08_01_page06.jpg"/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Captain Beaufort</persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Epping_ENK">Epping</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Essex_ENK">Essex -</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
